-- Ammtec, BHP, Leighton, Newcrest, Rio, Woodside: Australian Stock Preview
-- B y   S h a n i   R a j a
-- 2010-10-05T21:13:00Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-05/ammtec-bhp-leighton-newcrest-rio-woodside-australian-stock-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
whose shares may rise or fall in Australia. This preview
includes news announced after markets closed. All prices are
from yesterday’s close unless otherwise stated.  The S&P/ASX 200 Index  futures contract  due in December rose
1.4 percent to 4,691 as of 6:59 a.m. in Sydney. The  Bank of New
York Australia ADR Index  gained 2.4 percent. The  S&P/ASX 200
Index  slipped 0.4 percent to 4,606.90.  Mining shares: Copper rose to the highest price in 26
months as the dollar dropped. Futures for December delivery rose
1.7 percent to close at $3.7265 a pound at 1:32 p.m. in New York.  BHP Billiton Ltd.  (BHP AU), the world’s largest mining
company, fell 1.3 percent to A$39.50 in Sydney. Its American
depositary receipts climbed 2.4 percent in New York trading.  Rio Tinto Group  (RIO AU), the world’s third-biggest miner,
dropped 1.4 percent to A$77 in Sydney. Rio said it hasn’t made
any final decisions on its proposed iron-ore joint venture in
Western Australia with BHP.  Oil producers: Crude oil for November delivery increased
1.7 percent to $82.82 a barrel in New York, the highest
settlement since May 3.  Woodside Petroleum Ltd.  (WPL AU),
Australia’s second-biggest oil and gas producer, lost 1.1
percent to A$44.48.  Gold producers: Gold futures jumped to a record $1,342.60
an ounce in New York as the dollar sagged.  Newcrest Mining Ltd.  (NCM AU), Australia’s largest gold
producer, declined 0.3 percent to A$40.60.  St. Barbara Ltd.  (SBM
AU) advanced 3.9 percent to 40.5 Australian cents.  Ammtec Ltd.  (AEC AU): The Australian company that provides
metallurgical and mineral testing services said all its
directors, holding 4.6 percent of Ammtec’s outstanding shares,
accepted a revised takeover offer from Campbell Brothers Ltd.
subsidiary, Australian Laboratory Services Ltd. Ammtec rose 1.6
percent to A$3.94.       Leighton Holdings Ltd.  (LEI AU): Australia’s biggest
construction company urged shareholders to take no action after
Actividades de Construccion & Servicios SA made a takeover bid
for its majority shareholder, Germany’s Hochtief AG. Leighton’s
shares rose 1.3 percent to A$34.24.  To contact the reporter for this story:
 Shani Raja  in Sydney at 
 sraja4@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Darren Boey at 
 dboey@bloomberg.net . 